sentence: Tom Fogerty was born in Berkeley, California, United States.
Tom's band, Spider Webb and the Insects (which featured Jeremy Levine of the Seeds), signed a recording contract with Del-Fi Records but broke up in 1959 before releasing any records.

During the few years of the life of CCR, Tom sang backing vocals and wrote songs, but only one of his songs from when CCR was named the Golliwogs ("Walking on the Water") was re-recorded and chosen to be put on CCR's debut album.
He remained with Fantasy Records and his 1971 solo debut album, Tom Fogerty, reached No. 78 on the Billboard 200 chart.
On the follow-up, Excalibur, Jerry Garcia and Merl Saunders played on the sessions.

Stu Cook and Doug Clifford (CCR's former bass guitarist and drummer) as well as John Fogerty performed on the 1974 follow-up album, Zephyr National.

The song "Mystic Isle Avalon" features a complete reunion of CCR though John Fogerty recorded his parts separately.
Cook and Clifford also backed Tom on his fourth LP release of 1974 titled Myopia.
Throughout the rest of the 1970s and 1980s, Tom Fogerty continued to record, both solo and as part of the group Ruby.
At the October 1980 reception for Tom's marriage to Tricia Clapper, all four members of CCR reunited and performed for the first time in a decade.
Tom Fogerty lived in Scottsdale, Arizona, for the remainder of his life.
After his death, a music compilation titled The Very Best of Tom Fogerty was released.
Fogerty was survived by his second wife Tricia Clapper and six children.
